''[[Querelle]]''|''[[Cross of Iron]]''}}\n|-\n! rowspan=24 style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\"| [[Deaths in March 2020|March]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |''2''||[[James Lipton]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 93 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Writer, Actor ||{{hlist| ''[[Bewitched (2005 film)|Bewitched]]''|''[[Bolt (2008 film)|Bolt]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''3'' || [[Bo\u017eidar Ali\u0107]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 65 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Croatian || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Operation Stadium]]''|''[[The Third Key]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''6'' || [[David Paul (actor)|David Paul]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 62 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[The Barbarians (1987 film)|The Barbarians]]''|''[[D.C. Cab]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''7'' || [[Mart Crowley]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 84 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Screenwriter, Actor || {{hlist| ''[[The Boys in the Band (1970 film)|The Boys in the Band]]''|''[[The Celluloid Closet]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''8'' || [[Max von Sydow]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 90 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Swedish || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]''|''[[The Seventh Seal]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''11'' || [[Didier Bezace]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 74 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| French || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Thieves (1996 film)|Thieves]]''|''[[The Minister]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''12'' || [[Gary B. Kibbe]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 79 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Cinematographer || {{hlist| ''[[Escape from L.A.]]''|''[[They Live]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''12'' || [[Tonie Marshall]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 68 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| French || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress, Director, Screenwriter || {{hlist| ''[[Venus Beauty Institute]]''|''[[The Missionaries]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''15'' || [[Suzy Delair]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 102 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| French || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress, Singer || {{hlist| ''[[Quai des Orf\u00e8vres]]''|''[[Rocco and His Brothers]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''15'' || [[Roy Hudd]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 83 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| English || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[The Blood Beast Terror]]''|''[[Up the Chastity Belt]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''16'' || [[Stuart Whitman]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 92 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[The Comancheros (film)|The Comancheros]]''|''[[The Longest Day (film)|The Longest Day]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''17'' || [[Lyle Waggoner]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 84 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Love Me Deadly]]''|''[[Catalina Caper]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''19'' || [[Nazzareno Zamperla]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 82 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Italian || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor, Stuntman || {{hlist| ''[[Blood for a Silver Dollar]]''|''[[Sandokan the Great (film)|Sandokan the Great]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''23'' || [[Lucia Bos\u00e8]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 89 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Italian || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress || {{hlist| ''[[Story of a Love Affair]]''|''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (film)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''23'' || [[David Collings]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 79 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| English || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Scrooge (1970 film)|Scrooge]]''|''[[The Thirty Nine Steps (1978 film)|The Thirty Nine Steps]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''23'' || [[Alfio Contini]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 92 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Italian || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Cinematographer || {{hlist| ''[[Zabriskie Point (film)|Zabriskie Point]]''|''[[The Night Porter]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''24'' || [[Stuart Gordon]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 72 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Director, Screenwriter || {{hlist| ''[[Re-Animator]]''|''[[Fortress (1992 film)|Fortress]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''24'' || [[Terrence McNally]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 81 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Screenwriter || {{hlist| ''[[Frankie and Johnny (1991 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]''|''[[The Ritz (film)|The Ritz]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''24'' || [[Gerard Schurmann]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 96 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| English || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Composer || {{hlist| ''[[The Bedford Incident]]''|''[[The Lost Continent (1968 film)|The Lost Continent]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''24'' || [[Albert Uderzo]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 92 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| French || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Director, Screenwriter || {{hlist| ''[[Asterix and Cleopatra (film)|Asterix and Cleopatra]]''|''[[The Twelve Tasks of Asterix]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''26'' || [[Mark Blum]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 69 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Crocodile Dundee]]''|''[[Desperately Seeking Susan]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''28'' || [[Barbara R\u00fctting]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 92 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| German || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress || {{hlist| ''[[Operation Crossbow (film)|Operation Crossbow]]''|''[[Neues vom Hexer]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''31'' || [[Julie Bennett]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 88 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress, Voice Actress || {{hlist| ''[[Gay Purr-ee]]''|''[[Hey There, It's Yogi Bear]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''31'' || [[Andrew Jack (dialect coach)|Andrew Jack]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 76 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| English || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Dialect Coach, Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]''|''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]''}}\n|-\n! rowspan=32 style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\"| [[Deaths in April 2020|April]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''1'' || [[Adam Schlesinger]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 52 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Musician, Songwriter || {{hlist| ''[[That Thing You Do!]]''|''[[Music and Lyrics]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''4'' || [[Jay Benedict]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 68 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Victor/Victoria]]''|''[[Carmen (2003 film)|Carmen]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''4'' || [[Carlo Leva]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 90 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Italian || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Production Designer || {{hlist| ''[[The Cat o' Nine Tails]]''|''[[The Witness (1978 film)|The Witness]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''5'' || [[Shirley Douglas]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 86 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Canadian || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress || {{hlist| ''[[Lolita (1962 film)|Lolita]]''|''[[Dead Ringers (film)| Dead Ringers]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''6'' || [[Honor Blackman]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 94 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| English || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actress || {{hlist| ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]''|''[[Jason and the Argonauts (1963 film)| Jason and the Argonauts]]''}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''6'' || [[James Drury]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 85 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| American || style=\"text-align:center;\" | Actor || {{hlist| ''[[Pollyanna (1960 film)|Pollyanna]]''|''[[Ride the High Country]]''}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2020 films}}\n{{Portal bar|Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020 in film}}\n[[Category:Film by year]]\n[[Category:2020 in film]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeaths", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_film"}
{"title_page": "List of motets by Johann Sebastian Bach", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied.JPEG|thumb|upright=1.35|Bach's autograph of the motet {{lang|de|[[Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225|Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied]]}}, BWV 225]]\n{{Lists of compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n\nIt is uncertain how many [[motet]]s [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] composed, because some have been lost, and there are some doubtful attributions among the surviving ones associated with him. There is a case for regarding the six motets catalogued [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 225\u2013230 as being authenticated, although there is some doubt about one of them, [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'']]. A seventh motet, [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]], which was formerly attributed to Bach's older cousin [[Johann Christoph Bach]], appears to be at least partly by Bach, and if so was probably composed during his Weimar period.\n\n[[BWV 228]] is another motet which appears to have been written at [[Weimar]], between 1708 and 1717, the others were composed in [[Leipzig]]. \nSeveral of the motets were written for funerals. There is some uncertainty as to the extent that motets would have been called for in normal church services - there is evidence that it was considered an archaic form. The text of [[Jauchzet dem Herrn, alle Welt, BWV Anh. 160|''Jauchzet dem Herrn, alle Welt'', BWV Anh. 160]] (whether or not the piece is attributable to Bach) suggests a performance at Christmas. Another possible use is a pedagogical one, Bach's biographer [[Johann Nikolaus Forkel]] suggested that the choral writing would have been useful for training Bach's young singers, and Christoph Wolff has argued that this could apply in particular to [[Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225|''Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied'']].<ref>Wolff, Christoph.  ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=YtJVFiHnepcC&pg=PA249 Johann Sebastian Bach: The Learned Musician]'', p. 249 (W. W. Norton & Company 2001).</ref>\n\nBach's motets are his only vocal works that kept repertoire without interruption between his death in 1750 and the 19th-century [[Bach Revival]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Spitta |first=Philipp |authorlink=Philipp Spitta |title=Johann Sebastian Bach: His Work and Influence on the Music of Germany, 1685\u20131750 (Volume 2) |location=London |publisher=[[Novello & Co]] |year=1899 |url=https://archive.org/details/johannsebastianb02spituoft}}, [https://archive.org/stream/johannsebastianb02spituoft#page/611/mode/1up p. 611]</ref> In the early 19th century six motets (BWV 225, 228, Anh. 159, 229, 227, 226)<ref name=\"BH\"></ref><ref>{{OCLC|18856743}} at {{url|www.worldcat.org}}</ref> were among Bach's first printed music, after the second half of the 18th century when the only vocal music by Bach that was printed were collections of [[List of chorale harmonisations by Johann Sebastian Bach|his four-part chorales]].<ref>[[Johann Nikolaus Forkel|Forkel, Johann Nikolaus]], translated by [[Charles Sanford Terry (historian)|Charles Sanford Terry]] (1920). [https://archive.org/details/johannsebastian01terrgoog ''Johann Sebastian Bach: His Life, Art, and Work''.] New York: Harcourt, Brace and Howe; London: Constable, [https://archive.org/stream/johannsebastian01terrgoog#page/n22/mode/1up p. xvii]</ref>\n\n==BWV 225\u2013230==\n* {{lang|de|[[Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225|Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied]]}} (Sing unto the Lord a new song), BWV 225, is a motet in [[B-flat major]] scored for two four-part choirs ([[SATB]]) which was first performed in [[Leipzig]] around 1727. This motet uses [[Psalm 149]]:1\u20133 for its first movement, the third stanza of \"[[Nun lob, mein Seel, den Herren]]\" (a 1530 [[hymn]] after [[Psalm 103]] by [[Johann Gramann]]) for the second movement, and [[Psalm 150]]:2 and 6 for its third movement.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=228}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf]]}} (The Spirit gives aid to our weakness), BWV 226, a motet in B-flat major scored for two four-part choirs, was performed in Leipzig in 1729 for the funeral of [[Johann Heinrich Ernesti]]. The text is taken from the [[Epistle to the Romans]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Romans|chapter=8|verse=26|range=\u201327}}) and [[Martin Luther]]'s third stanza to the hymn \"{{lang|de|[[Komm, Heiliger Geist, Herre Gott]]|italic=no}}\" (1524).{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|Jesu, meine Freude]]}} (Jesus, my joy), BWV 227, is a motet in [[E minor]] for five vocal parts. It has been suggested{{by whom|date=March 2020}} that it was composed in 1723 for the funeral of Johanna Maria K\u00e4sin, the wife of the Leipzig postmaster. It takes its title from the hymn \"[[Jesu, meine Freude]]\" by [[Johann Franck]] on which it is based. The stanzas of the chorale are interspersed with passages from the [[Epistle to the Romans]]. The chorale melody on which several movements are based was by [[Johann Cr\u00fcger]] (1653). The German text is by [[Johann Franck]], and dates from {{circa|1650}}.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, BWV 228|F\u00fcrchte dich nicht]]}} (Do not fear), BWV 228, is a motet in [[A major]] for a funeral, set for double chorus and unspecified instruments playing [[colla parte]]. The work in two movements draws its text from the [[Book of Isaiah]] and a hymn by [[Paul Gerhardt]]. Traditionally, scholars believed that Bach composed it in Leipzig in 1726, while more recent scholarship suggests for stylistic reasons that it was already composed during Bach's Weimar period. It has been compared to another motet for double choir [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]], which is possibly by Bach.<ref name=\"Gardiner\">{{cite web | url=http://www.monteverdi.org.uk/downloads/booklets/sdg716.pdf | title=Bach Motets | accessdate=9 September 2015 | author=Gardiner, John Eliot | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304203735/http://www.monteverdi.org.uk/downloads/booklets/sdg716.pdf | archive-date=4 March 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{lang|de|[[Komm, Jesu, komm, BWV 229|Komm, Jesu, komm]]}} (Come, Jesus, come), BWV 229, is a motet in [[G minor]] composed in Leipzig, which received its first performance by 1731\u20131732.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden]]}} (Praise the Lord, all ye heathen), BWV 230, is a motet in [[C major]] scored for four voices, which draws its text from [[Psalm 117]]:[[s:Bible (King James)/Psalms#117:1|1\u20132]]. Although some scholars have expressed doubts about the attribution to Bach, the work is generally regarded as a surviving motet by Bach.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==BWV 28/2a (231) and 118==\n* {{lang|de|{{ill|Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren, BWV 28/2a|scores|3=Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren, BWV 231 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|lt=Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren}}}}, originally BWV 231, later renumbered to BWV 28/2a, is the second movement of the motet {{lang|de|[[Jauchzet dem Herrn alle Welt]]}} presented as a separate motet. Whether Bach extracted this motet (which is based on the second movement of the cantata [[BWV 28]]) from the three-movement motet or the cantata, and/or used it as a separate motet is not known.{{sfn|Melamed|1995|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA89 89\u201397]}}<ref name=BDW0036>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|0036}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Boyd|first=Malcolm|title=Oxford Composer Companions: J.S. Bach|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|isbn=0-19-866208-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/jsbach0000unse/page/245 245]|url=https://archive.org/details/jsbach0000unse/page/245}}</ref>\n* [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]]: originally listed as a cantata, in BWV<sup>2a</sup> listed as a (funeral) motet.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=233}}<ref name=BDW0143>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|0143}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n\n==BWV Anh. 159\u2013165==\n* {{lang|de|[[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|Ich lasse dich nicht]]}} (I will not let you go [unless you bless me]), BWV Anh. 159, is a motet in [[F minor]] scored for double chorus, [[SATB]]\u2014SATB and unspecified instruments playing [[colla parte]]. The motet, which was formerly attributed to Bach's older cousin [[Johann Christoph Bach]], appears to be one of Bach's earlier works, possibly composed during his [[Weimar]] period around 1712.<ref name=\"Gardiner\" /> Consequently, the motet was moved from [[BWV Anh.]] III (spurious works) to BWV Anh. II (doubtful works) in BWV<sup>2a</sup>.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=459}} The final chorale of the motet is an adaptation of [[BWV 421]], but that may also be a later addition to the motet.<ref name=BDW1470>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1470}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref> It draws its text from a verse taken from the [[Book of Genesis]], from the scene of [[Jacob's Ladder]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Genesis|chapter=32|verse=27}}), combined with the third stanza of the [[hymn]] \"[[Warum betr\u00fcbst du dich, mein Herz]]\" by [[Erasmus Alberus]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Jauchzet dem Herrn alle Welt]]}}, BWV Anh. 160 (=[[Georg Philipp Telemann#Partial list of works|TWV]] 8:10) is a three-movement [[pasticcio]] motet for SATB\u2014SATB attributed to, among others, Bach and [[Georg Philipp Telemann]]. All that is certain regarding Bach's participation in the work is that its second movement derives from the second movement of Bach's cantata [[BWV 28]].{{sfn|Melamed|1995|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA89 89\u201397]}}<ref name=BDW1471>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1471}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* [[BWV Anh. 161|Motet&nbsp;movement ''K\u00fcndlich gro\u00df ist das gottselige Geheimnis'']], BWV Anh. 161, in [[D major]] for SATB, strings(?) and continuo, by Graun (possibly [[Carl Heinrich Graun]]), precedes laudes [[Magnificat (Bach)#A. Vom Himmel hoch|A]] and [[Magnificat (Bach)#B. Freut euch und jubiliert|B]] of [[Magnificat (Bach)|Bach's Magnificat]] in a three-movement Christmas motet pasticcio.<ref name=BDW1472>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1472}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* ''Lob und Ehre und Weisheit und Dank'', BWV Anh. 162, for SATB\u2014SATB, by [[Georg Gottfried Wagner]].<ref>[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWVAnh162.htm Georg Gottfried Wagner: Motet Lob und Ehre und Weisheit, BWV Anh 162] at {{url|www.bach-cantatas.com}}</ref><ref name=BDW1473>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1473}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* ''Merk auf, mein Herz, und sieh dorthin'', BWV Anh. 163, for SATB\u2014SATB, by [[Johann Bernhard Bach|Johann Bernhard]] or [[Johann Ernst Bach (musician at Saxe-Weimar)|Johann Ernst]] Bach.<ref>[http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00000248 BR Bruxelles ''Ms. II 3902 Mus.'']  at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref name=BDW1474>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1474}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* [[Nun danket alle Gott, BWV Anh. 164|''Nun danket alle Gott'', BWV&nbsp;Anh.&nbsp;164]], for SSATB, by [[Johann Christoph Altnickol]], Bach's son-in-law.<ref>[http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002751 HLB Darmstadt, ''Mus. ms. 521/1''] and [http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002752 HLB Darmstadt, ''Mus. ms. 521/2\u20136''] at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref name=BDW1475>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1475}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* [[Unser Wandel ist im Himmel, BWV Anh. 165|''Unser Wandel ist im Himmel'', BWV Anh. 165]], for SATB, after movements 2, 4 and 6 of cantata [[Mein Odem ist schwach, BWV 222|''Mein Odem ist schwach'', BWV 222]], by [[Johann Ernst Bach (musician at Saxe-Weimar)|Johann Ernst Bach]].<ref>[http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002798 HLB Darmstadt, ''Mus. ms. 528''] at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref name=BDW1476>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1476}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n\n==BWV deest==\n{{See also|The righteous perishes#In Lutheranism}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Der Gerechte kommt um]]}}, BWV deest, a chorale from a pasticcio [[passion oratorio]], is a [[parody (music)|parody]] of the motet ''[[Tristis est anima mea (attributed to Kuhnau)|Tristis est anima mea]]'' which was likely composed by [[Johann Kuhnau]]. The arrangement is possibly Bach's, and possibly Bach used it as a separate (funeral) motet.<ref name=BDW1532>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1532}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>{{sfn|Melamed|1995|pp=[https://books.google.de/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA148 148\u2013149]}}\n\n==Motets listed in the second chapter of the ''Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis'' (1998)==\n{{Bach's compositions (legend)}}\n{{Bach's compositions (scoring)}}\n{{Bach's compositions (background)}}\n{{Bach's compositions (header)|Motets listed in Chapter 2 of BWV<sup>2a</sup>}}<onlyinclude>\n|- style=\"background: #E3F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0225.000\" | 225\n| data-sort-value=\"228.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1727-01-01\" | 1726\u20131727<br />New Year?\n| [[BWV 225|Motet ''Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied'']]\n| B\u266d&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 +colla parte instruments?\" | 2SATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?)\n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 003\" | [[scores:Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 3]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 001\" | [[scores:Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 1]]\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 8244]] (/2); text after [[Psalm 149|Ps. 149]]: 1\u20133 (/1), by [[Johann Gramann|Gramann]] after [[Psalm 103|Ps. 103]] (/2), after [[Psalm 150|Ps. 150]]: 2, 6 (/3){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0282}}\n|- style=\"background: #E3F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0226.000\" | 226\n| data-sort-value=\"229.001\" | 2.\n| 1729-10-20\n| [[BWV 226|Motet ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'']] (funeral of [[Johann Heinrich Ernesti|Ernesti, J.&nbsp;H.]])\n| B\u266d&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 Str Vc Obx2 Tai Bas\" | 2SATB Str Vc 2Ob Tai Bas \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 039\" | [[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Vocal_Scores|39: 39]], [[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|143]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 037\" | [[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 37]]<br />[[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Other|III/2.1:&nbsp;18]]<br />III/2.2:&nbsp;38\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 7445a]] (/2); text after [[Epistle to the Romans|Rom.]] 8: 26\u201327 (/1), by [[Martin Luther|Luther]] (/2){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| data-sort-value=\"00283\" | {{BDW|0283}}<br />{{BDW|1182|1}}\n|- style=\"background: #F5F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0227.000\" | 227\n| data-sort-value=\"229.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1728-07-18\" | {{circa|1723\u20131735}}\n| [[BWV 227|Motet ''Jesu, meine Freude'']]\n| E&nbsp;min.\n| data-sort-value=\"SSATB +colla parte instruments?\" | SSATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 059\" | [[scores:Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 59]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 075\" | [[scores:Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 75]]<br />[[scores:Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Other|III/2.1:&nbsp;27,<br />28,&nbsp;22]]<br />III/2.2: 156, 168\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 8032]] (odd [[movement (music)|mvt]]s); text by [[Johann Franck|Franck, J.]] (odd mvts), after [[Epistle to the Romans|Rom.]] 8: 1\u20132, 9\u201311 (even mvts){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| data-sort-value=\"00284\" | {{BDW|0284}}<br />{{BDW|1200|1}}<br />{{BDW|1201|1}}<br />{{BDW|1202|1}}\n|- \n| data-sort-value=\"0228.000\" | 228\n| data-sort-value=\"231.001\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1715-07-01\" | {{circa|1715}}\n| [[BWV 228|Motet ''F\u00fcrchte dich nicht'']]\n| A&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 +colla parte instruments?\" | 2SATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 087\" | [[scores:F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, ich bin bei dir, BWV 228 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 85]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 107\" | [[scores:F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, ich bin bei dir, BWV 228 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 105]]\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 6461]] (/2); text after [[Book of Isaiah|Is.]] 41: 10 (/1), 43: 1 (/2), by [[Paul Gerhardt|Gerhardt]] (/2){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0285}}\n|- style=\"background: #F6E3CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0229.000\" | 229\n| data-sort-value=\"231.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1730-07-01\" | before 1731\u20131732\n| [[BWV 229|Motet ''Komm, Jesu, komm'']]\n| G&nbsp;min.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 +colla parte instruments\" | 2SATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 109\" | [[scores:Komm, Jesu, komm, BWV 229 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 107]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 127\" | [[scores:Komm, Jesu, komm, BWV 229 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 125]]\n| text by [[Paul Thymich|Thymich]]{{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0286}}\n|- style=\"background: #F5F6CE;\" \n| data-sort-value=\"0230.000\" | 230\n| data-sort-value=\"232.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1730-07-01\" | 1723\u20131739?\n| [[BWV 230|Motet ''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'']]\n| C&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATB Bc +colla parte instruments?\" | SATB Bc (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 129\" | [[scores:Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 127]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 149\" | [[scores:Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 147]]\n| text after [[Psalm 117|Ps. 117]]{{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0287}}\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"0231.000\" | 231\n| data-sort-value=\"233.001\" | \n----\n|\n----\n| data-sort-value=\"Motet Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren\" | \n----\n| \n----\n| \n----\n| \n----\n| \n----\n| see [[BWV 28/2a]]\n| {{BDW|0288}}\n|- style=\"background: #E3F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0118.100\" | 118.1\n| data-sort-value=\"233.003\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1736-12-31\" | 1736\u20131737\n| [[BWV 118|Motet ''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'']] (funeral)\n| B\u266d&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATB Hnx2 Cnt Tbnx3\" | SATB 2Hn Cnt 3Tbn \n| data-sort-value=\"000.24: 185\" | [[scores:O Jesu Christ, mein's Lebens Licht, BWV 118 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|24:&nbsp;185]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 163\" | [[scores:O Jesu Christ, mein's Lebens Licht, BWV 118 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1:&nbsp;163]]\n| text by [[Martin Behm|Behm]]; \u2192 [[BWV 118]].2{{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0143}}\n|- style=\"background: #E3F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0118.200\" | 118.2\n| data-sort-value=\"233.004\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1746-12-31\" | 1746\u20131747\n| [[BWV 118|Motet ''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'']] (funeral)\n| B\u266d&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATB Obx2 Tai Bas Hnx2 Str Bc\" | SATB 2Ob Tai Bas 2Hn Str Bc\n| data-sort-value=\"000.67 1: 000\" | [[scores:O Jesu Christ, mein's Lebens Licht, BWV 118 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|NBG&nbsp;17<sup>1</sup>]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 171\" | [[scores:O Jesu Christ, mein's Lebens Licht, BWV 118 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1:&nbsp;171]]\n| text by [[Martin Behm|Behm]]; after [[BWV 118]].1{{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|1121|1}}</onlyinclude>\n|}\n\n==Publication and recording==\n{{more sources|section|date=March 2020}}\n===Publications===\n[[St. Thomas School, Leipzig]], appears to have kept the{{which|date=March 2020}} motets in the repertory of its [[Thomanerchor]] after Bach's death. It is documented that the choir performed ''Singet dem Herrn'' for Mozart in 1789.\nThe director on this occasion was the ''[[Thomaskantor]]'' [[Johann Friedrich Doles]], a pupil of Bach.\nThe interest in Bach motets was sufficient for six of them to be printed for the first time in 1802/1803. They appeared in two volumes from the Leipzig publisher [[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]]. The editor is not credited on the title-page;<ref name=\"BH\">Johann Gottfried Schicht, editor. [https://archive.org/details/johsebbachsmotet00bach ''Joh. Seb. Bach's Motetten in Partitur''.] Leipzig: [[Breitkopf und H\u00e4rtel]]. 1802 (Vol. 1: BWV 225, 228, Anh. 159); 1803 (Vol.2: BWV 229, 227, 226).</ref> however, it has been suggested{{by whom|date=March 2020}} that the person responsible was [[Johann Gottfried Schicht]] who was active in the city as a choral and orchestral conductor.\n\nBook I consisted of\n*''Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied'' (BWV 225)\n*''F\u00fcrchte dich nicht'' (BWV 228)\n*''Ich lasse dich nicht'' (BWV Anh. 159)\n\nBook II consisted of\n*''Komm, Jesu, komm'' (BWV 229)\n*''Jesu, meine Freude'' (BWV 227)\n*''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'' (BWV 228)  \n\nIn 1892 the motets were published as part of the [[Bach-Gesellschaft-Ausgabe]], the first edition of the composer's complete works. The editor was [[Franz W\u00fcllner]], who did not accept Bach's authorship of ''Ich Lasse dich nicht''.<ref>Melamed, Daniel R. \u201cThe Authorship of the Motet \u2018Ich Lasse Dich Nicht\u2019 (BWV Anh. 159).\u201d Journal of the American Musicological Society, vol. 41, no. 3, 1988, pp. 491\u2013526. JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/831462. Accessed 30 Mar. 2020 (subscription required).</ref>\nThe  motet volume of the [[New Bach Edition]] (the second edition of the composer's complete works) came out in 1965. It includes ''O Jesu Christ, mein Lebens Licht'' (which had been included among the cantatas in the Bach-Gesellschaft-Ausgabe) and ''Lobet den Herrn''.\nThe motets were published by [[Carus-Verlag]] in 1975, edited by [[G\u00fcnter Graulich]], and again in 2003, seven compositions edited by [[Uwe Wolf (musicologist)|Uwe Wolf]].{{sfn|Wolf|2002|p=I}}\n\n===Recordings===\nMost recordings of BWV 225-230 have been made since the Second World War. The Thomanerchor, for example, recorded the set in the 1950s.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> However, there were several pre-War recordings of the motets. The first recording of a Bach motet was a 1927 version of ''Jesu Meine Freude''.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nOne of the decisions which needs to be made is how many voices to use per part. The motets have been recorded with [[one voice per part]] by [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]]. Most recordings deploy more than one singer per part; for example, [[Masaaki Suzuki]] and his [[Bach Collegium Japan]] use a chorus of eighteen singers.<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach - Motets |website=Bis |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets have also been recorded by the British group [[The Sixteen]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book |date=1998 |editor1-last=D\u00fcrr |editor1-first=Alfred |editor1-link=Alfred D\u00fcrr |editor2-last=Kobayashi |editor2-first=Yoshitake |title=Bach Werke Verzeichnis: Kleine Ausgabe \u2013 Nach der von Wolfgang Schmieder vorgelegten 2. Ausgabe |trans-title=Bach Works Catalogue: Small Edition \u2013 After Wolfgang Schmieder's 2nd edition |language=de |others=Kirsten Bei\u00dfwenger (collaborator). |title-link=Bach Werke Verzeichnis |edition=[[BWV2a|BWV<sup>2a</sup>]] |location=Wiesbaden |publisher=[[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]] |isbn=9783765102493 |postscript=. Preface in English and German. |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Melamed\n| first = Daniel R.\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC\n| title = J.S. Bach and the German Motet\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press\n| year = 1995\n| isbn = 0-52-141864-X<!-- 9780521418645 -->\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last = \n| first = \n| authorlink = \n| editor-last = Wolf\n| editor-first = Uwe\n| editor-link = Uwe Wolf (musicologist)\n| url = https://www.carusmedia.com/images-intern/medien/30/3122410/3122410x.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach / Motetten / Motets\n| website = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| date = 2002\n| page = V\n| accessdate = 24 March 2020\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Motets%2C_BWV_225-231_%28Bach%2C_Johann_Sebastian%29|cname=Motets by Johan Sebastian Bach}}\n* [[Johann Gottfried Schicht]], editor. [https://archive.org/details/johsebbachsmotet00bach ''Joh. Seb. Bach's Motetten in Partitur''.] Leipzig: [[Breitkopf und H\u00e4rtel]]. 1802 (Vol. 1: BWV 225, 228, Anh. 159); 1803 (Vol.2: BWV 229, 227, 226)\n* [[Uwe Wolf (musicologist)|Uwe Wolf]]: [https://books.google.com/books?id=1mPrDGN3bpQC&pg=PA269 \"Zur Schichtschen Typendruck-Ausgabe der Motetten Johann Sebastian Bachs und zu ihrer Stellung in der Werk\u00fcberlieferung\"] in [https://books.google.com/books?id=1mPrDGN3bpQC ''Musikalische Quellen, Quellen zur Musikgeschichte: Festschrift f\u00fcr Martin Staehelin zum 65. Geburtstag''.] Edited by J\u00fcrgen Heidrich, [[Hans Joachim Marx]] and [[Ulrich Konrad]]. Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht. 2002. {{ISBN|9783525278208}}, {{Page numbers|269\u2013286}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Bach motets}}\n{{Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n\n[[Category:Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach|Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach, List of]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied.JPEG|thumb|upright=1.35|Bach's autograph of the motet {{lang|de|[[Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225|Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied]]}}, BWV 225]]\n{{Lists of compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n\nIt is uncertain how many [[motet]]s [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] composed, because some have been lost, and there are some doubtful attributions among the surviving ones associated with him. There is a case for regarding the six motets catalogued [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV]] 225\u2013230 as being authenticated, although there is some doubt about one of them, [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'']]. A seventh motet, [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]], which was formerly attributed to Bach's older cousin [[Johann Christoph Bach]], appears to be at least partly by Bach, and if so was probably composed during his Weimar period.\n\n[[BWV 228]] is another motet which appears to have been written at [[Weimar]], between 1708 and 1717, the others were composed in [[Leipzig]]. \nSeveral of the motets were written for funerals. There is some uncertainty as to the extent that motets would have been called for in normal church services - there is evidence that it was considered an archaic form. The text of [[Jauchzet dem Herrn, alle Welt, BWV Anh. 160|''Jauchzet dem Herrn, alle Welt'', BWV Anh. 160]] (whether or not the piece is attributable to Bach) suggests a performance at Christmas. Another possible use is a pedagogical one, Bach's biographer [[Johann Nikolaus Forkel]] suggested that the choral writing would have been useful for training Bach's young singers, and Christoph Wolff has argued that this could apply in particular to [[Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225|''Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied'']].<ref>Wolff, Christoph.  ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=YtJVFiHnepcC&pg=PA249 Johann Sebastian Bach: The Learned Musician]'', p. 249 (W. W. Norton & Company 2001).</ref>\n\nBach's motets are his only vocal works that kept repertoire without interruption between his death in 1750 and the 19th-century [[Bach Revival]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Spitta |first=Philipp |authorlink=Philipp Spitta |title=Johann Sebastian Bach: His Work and Influence on the Music of Germany, 1685\u20131750 (Volume 2) |location=London |publisher=[[Novello & Co]] |year=1899 |url=https://archive.org/details/johannsebastianb02spituoft}}, [https://archive.org/stream/johannsebastianb02spituoft#page/611/mode/1up p. 611]</ref> In the early 19th century six motets (BWV 225, 228, Anh. 159, 229, 227, 226)<ref name=\"BH\"></ref><ref>{{OCLC|18856743}} at {{url|www.worldcat.org}}</ref> were among Bach's first printed music, after the second half of the 18th century when the only vocal music by Bach that was printed were collections of [[List of chorale harmonisations by Johann Sebastian Bach|his four-part chorales]].<ref>[[Johann Nikolaus Forkel|Forkel, Johann Nikolaus]], translated by [[Charles Sanford Terry (historian)|Charles Sanford Terry]] (1920). [https://archive.org/details/johannsebastian01terrgoog ''Johann Sebastian Bach: His Life, Art, and Work''.] New York: Harcourt, Brace and Howe; London: Constable, [https://archive.org/stream/johannsebastian01terrgoog#page/n22/mode/1up p. xvii]</ref>\n\n==BWV 225\u2013230==\n* {{lang|de|[[Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225|Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied]]}} (Sing unto the Lord a new song), BWV 225, is a motet in [[B-flat major]] scored for two four-part choirs ([[SATB]]) which was first performed in [[Leipzig]] around 1727. This motet uses [[Psalm 149]]:1\u20133 for its first movement, the third stanza of \"[[Nun lob, mein Seel, den Herren]]\" (a 1530 [[hymn]] after [[Psalm 103]] by [[Johann Gramann]]) for the second movement, and [[Psalm 150]]:2 and 6 for its third movement.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=228}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf]]}} (The Spirit gives aid to our weakness), BWV 226, a motet in B-flat major scored for two four-part choirs, was performed in Leipzig in 1729 for the funeral of [[Johann Heinrich Ernesti]]. The text is taken from the [[Epistle to the Romans]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Romans|chapter=8|verse=26|range=\u201327}}) and [[Martin Luther]]'s third stanza to the hymn \"{{lang|de|[[Komm, Heiliger Geist, Herre Gott]]|italic=no}}\" (1524).{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|Jesu, meine Freude]]}} (Jesus, my joy), BWV 227, is a motet in [[E minor]] for five vocal parts. It has been suggested{{by whom|date=March 2020}} that it was composed in 1723 for the funeral of Johanna Maria K\u00e4sin, the wife of the Leipzig postmaster. It takes its title from the hymn \"[[Jesu, meine Freude]]\" by [[Johann Franck]] on which it is based. The stanzas of the chorale are interspersed with passages from the [[Epistle to the Romans]]. The chorale melody on which several movements are based was by [[Johann Cr\u00fcger]] (1653). The German text is by [[Johann Franck]], and dates from {{circa|1650}}.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, BWV 228|F\u00fcrchte dich nicht]]}} (Do not fear), BWV 228, is a motet in [[A major]] for a funeral, set for double chorus and unspecified instruments playing [[colla parte]]. The work in two movements draws its text from the [[Book of Isaiah]] and a hymn by [[Paul Gerhardt]]. Traditionally, scholars believed that Bach composed it in Leipzig in 1726, while more recent scholarship suggests for stylistic reasons that it was already composed during Bach's Weimar period. It has been compared to another motet for double choir [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]], which is possibly by Bach.<ref name=\"Gardiner\">{{cite web | url=http://www.monteverdi.org.uk/downloads/booklets/sdg716.pdf | title=Bach Motets | accessdate=9 September 2015 | author=Gardiner, John Eliot | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304203735/http://www.monteverdi.org.uk/downloads/booklets/sdg716.pdf | archive-date=4 March 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{lang|de|[[Komm, Jesu, komm, BWV 229|Komm, Jesu, komm]]}} (Come, Jesus, come), BWV 229, is a motet in [[G minor]] composed in Leipzig, which received its first performance by 1731\u20131732.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden]]}} (Praise the Lord, all ye heathen), BWV 230, is a motet in [[C major]] scored for four voices, which draws its text from [[Psalm 117]]:[[s:Bible (King James)/Psalms#117:1|1\u20132]]. Although some scholars have expressed doubts about the attribution to Bach, the work is generally regarded as a surviving motet by Bach.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==BWV 28/2a (231) and 118==\n* {{lang|de|{{ill|Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren, BWV 28/2a|scores|3=Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren, BWV 231 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|lt=Sei Lob und Preis mit Ehren}}}}, originally BWV 231, later renumbered to BWV 28/2a, is the second movement of the motet {{lang|de|[[Jauchzet dem Herrn alle Welt]]}} presented as a separate motet. Whether Bach extracted this motet (which is based on the second movement of the cantata [[BWV 28]]) from the three-movement motet or the cantata, and/or used it as a separate motet is not known.{{sfn|Melamed|1995|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA89 89\u201397]}}<ref name=BDW0036>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|0036}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Boyd|first=Malcolm|title=Oxford Composer Companions: J.S. Bach|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|isbn=0-19-866208-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/jsbach0000unse/page/245 245]|url=https://archive.org/details/jsbach0000unse/page/245}}</ref>\n* [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]]: originally listed as a cantata, in BWV<sup>2a</sup> listed as a (funeral) motet.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=233}}<ref name=BDW0143>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|0143}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n\n==BWV Anh. 159\u2013165==\n* {{lang|de|[[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|Ich lasse dich nicht]]}} (I will not let you go [unless you bless me]), BWV Anh. 159, is a motet in [[F minor]] scored for double chorus, [[SATB]]\u2014SATB and unspecified instruments playing [[colla parte]]. The motet, which was formerly attributed to Bach's older cousin [[Johann Christoph Bach]], appears to be one of Bach's earlier works, possibly composed during his [[Weimar]] period around 1712.<ref name=\"Gardiner\" /> Consequently, the motet was moved from [[BWV Anh.]] III (spurious works) to BWV Anh. II (doubtful works) in BWV<sup>2a</sup>.{{sfn|D\u00fcrr|Kobayashi|1998|p=459}} The final chorale of the motet is an adaptation of [[BWV 421]], but that may also be a later addition to the motet.<ref name=BDW1470>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1470}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref> It draws its text from a verse taken from the [[Book of Genesis]], from the scene of [[Jacob's Ladder]] ({{Sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Genesis|chapter=32|verse=27}}), combined with the third stanza of the [[hymn]] \"[[Warum betr\u00fcbst du dich, mein Herz]]\" by [[Erasmus Alberus]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Jauchzet dem Herrn alle Welt]]}}, BWV Anh. 160 (=[[Georg Philipp Telemann#Partial list of works|TWV]] 8:10) is a three-movement [[pasticcio]] motet for SATB\u2014SATB attributed to, among others, Bach and [[Georg Philipp Telemann]]. All that is certain regarding Bach's participation in the work is that its second movement derives from the second movement of Bach's cantata [[BWV 28]].{{sfn|Melamed|1995|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA89 89\u201397]}}<ref name=BDW1471>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1471}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* [[BWV Anh. 161|Motet&nbsp;movement ''K\u00fcndlich gro\u00df ist das gottselige Geheimnis'']], BWV Anh. 161, in [[D major]] for SATB, strings(?) and continuo, by Graun (possibly [[Carl Heinrich Graun]]), precedes laudes [[Magnificat (Bach)#A. Vom Himmel hoch|A]] and [[Magnificat (Bach)#B. Freut euch und jubiliert|B]] of [[Magnificat (Bach)|Bach's Magnificat]] in a three-movement Christmas motet pasticcio.<ref name=BDW1472>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1472}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* ''Lob und Ehre und Weisheit und Dank'', BWV Anh. 162, for SATB\u2014SATB, by [[Georg Gottfried Wagner]].<ref>[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWVAnh162.htm Georg Gottfried Wagner: Motet Lob und Ehre und Weisheit, BWV Anh 162] at {{url|www.bach-cantatas.com}}</ref><ref name=BDW1473>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1473}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* ''Merk auf, mein Herz, und sieh dorthin'', BWV Anh. 163, for SATB\u2014SATB, by [[Johann Bernhard Bach|Johann Bernhard]] or [[Johann Ernst Bach (musician at Saxe-Weimar)|Johann Ernst]] Bach.<ref>[http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00000248 BR Bruxelles ''Ms. II 3902 Mus.'']  at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref name=BDW1474>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1474}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* [[Nun danket alle Gott, BWV Anh. 164|''Nun danket alle Gott'', BWV&nbsp;Anh.&nbsp;164]], for SSATB, by [[Johann Christoph Altnickol]], Bach's son-in-law.<ref>[http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002751 HLB Darmstadt, ''Mus. ms. 521/1''] and [http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002752 HLB Darmstadt, ''Mus. ms. 521/2\u20136''] at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref name=BDW1475>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1475}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n* [[Unser Wandel ist im Himmel, BWV Anh. 165|''Unser Wandel ist im Himmel'', BWV Anh. 165]], for SATB, after movements 2, 4 and 6 of cantata [[Mein Odem ist schwach, BWV 222|''Mein Odem ist schwach'', BWV 222]], by [[Johann Ernst Bach (musician at Saxe-Weimar)|Johann Ernst Bach]].<ref>[http://www.bachdigital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002798 HLB Darmstadt, ''Mus. ms. 528''] at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref><ref name=BDW1476>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1476}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>\n\n==BWV deest==\n{{See also|The righteous perishes#In Lutheranism}}\n* {{lang|de|[[Der Gerechte kommt um]]}}, BWV deest, a chorale from a pasticcio [[passion oratorio]], is a [[parody (music)|parody]] of the motet ''[[Tristis est anima mea (attributed to Kuhnau)|Tristis est anima mea]]'' which was likely composed by [[Johann Kuhnau]]. The arrangement is possibly Bach's, and possibly Bach used it as a separate (funeral) motet.<ref name=BDW1532>Bach Digital Work {{BDW|1532}} at {{url|www.bachdigital.de}}</ref>{{sfn|Melamed|1995|pp=[https://books.google.de/books?id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA148 148\u2013149]}}\n\n==Motets listed in the second chapter of the ''Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis'' (1998)==\n{{Bach's compositions (legend)}}\n{{Bach's compositions (scoring)}}\n{{Bach's compositions (background)}}\n{{Bach's compositions (header)|Motets listed in Chapter 2 of BWV<sup>2a</sup>}}<onlyinclude>\n|- style=\"background: #E3F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0225.000\" | 225\n| data-sort-value=\"228.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1727-01-01\" | 1726\u20131727<br />New Year?\n| [[BWV 225|Motet ''Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied'']]\n| B\u266d&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 +colla parte instruments?\" | 2SATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?)\n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 003\" | [[scores:Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 3]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 001\" | [[scores:Singet dem Herrn ein neues Lied, BWV 225 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 1]]\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 8244]] (/2); text after [[Psalm 149|Ps. 149]]: 1\u20133 (/1), by [[Johann Gramann|Gramann]] after [[Psalm 103|Ps. 103]] (/2), after [[Psalm 150|Ps. 150]]: 2, 6 (/3){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0282}}\n|- style=\"background: #E3F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0226.000\" | 226\n| data-sort-value=\"229.001\" | 2.\n| 1729-10-20\n| [[BWV 226|Motet ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'']] (funeral of [[Johann Heinrich Ernesti|Ernesti, J.&nbsp;H.]])\n| B\u266d&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 Str Vc Obx2 Tai Bas\" | 2SATB Str Vc 2Ob Tai Bas \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 039\" | [[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Vocal_Scores|39: 39]], [[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|143]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 037\" | [[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 37]]<br />[[scores:Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Other|III/2.1:&nbsp;18]]<br />III/2.2:&nbsp;38\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 7445a]] (/2); text after [[Epistle to the Romans|Rom.]] 8: 26\u201327 (/1), by [[Martin Luther|Luther]] (/2){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| data-sort-value=\"00283\" | {{BDW|0283}}<br />{{BDW|1182|1}}\n|- style=\"background: #F5F6CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0227.000\" | 227\n| data-sort-value=\"229.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1728-07-18\" | {{circa|1723\u20131735}}\n| [[BWV 227|Motet ''Jesu, meine Freude'']]\n| E&nbsp;min.\n| data-sort-value=\"SSATB +colla parte instruments?\" | SSATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 059\" | [[scores:Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 59]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 075\" | [[scores:Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 75]]<br />[[scores:Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)#Other|III/2.1:&nbsp;27,<br />28,&nbsp;22]]<br />III/2.2: 156, 168\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 8032]] (odd [[movement (music)|mvt]]s); text by [[Johann Franck|Franck, J.]] (odd mvts), after [[Epistle to the Romans|Rom.]] 8: 1\u20132, 9\u201311 (even mvts){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| data-sort-value=\"00284\" | {{BDW|0284}}<br />{{BDW|1200|1}}<br />{{BDW|1201|1}}<br />{{BDW|1202|1}}\n|- \n| data-sort-value=\"0228.000\" | 228\n| data-sort-value=\"231.001\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1715-07-01\" | {{circa|1715}}\n| [[BWV 228|Motet ''F\u00fcrchte dich nicht'']]\n| A&nbsp;maj.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 +colla parte instruments?\" | 2SATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.?) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 087\" | [[scores:F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, ich bin bei dir, BWV 228 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 85]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 107\" | [[scores:F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, ich bin bei dir, BWV 228 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 105]]\n| after [[Zahn number|Z 6461]] (/2); text after [[Book of Isaiah|Is.]] 41: 10 (/1), 43: 1 (/2), by [[Paul Gerhardt|Gerhardt]] (/2){{sfn|Melamed|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=nl&id=JDlBMqI628UC&pg=PA102 102]}}\n| {{BDW|0285}}\n|- style=\"background: #F6E3CE;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"0229.000\" | 229\n| data-sort-value=\"231.002\" | 2.\n| data-sort-value=\"1730-07-01\" | before 1731\u20131732\n| [[BWV 229|Motet ''Komm, Jesu, komm'']]\n| G&nbsp;min.\n| data-sort-value=\"SATBx2 +colla parte instruments\" | 2SATB (+''[[colla parte]]'' instr.) \n| data-sort-value=\"000.39: 109\" | [[scores:Komm, Jesu, komm, BWV 229 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|39: 107]]\n| data-sort-value=\"III/01: 127\" | [[scores:Komm, Jesu, komm, BWV 229 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|III/1: 125]]\n|